> *"We don't ship features. We ship legends."*

---

## ⚡ gm, anon.

You've stumbled into **Terminal Myth** — where the code is dirty, the commits are unhinged, and the only thing we touch grass for is debugging production at 3am.

This ain't your corpo bootcamp GitHub repo.  
This is the **war room**.

---

## 🧬 what is this place

```bash
$ whoami
> degen. builder. myth-maker.

$ pwd
> /somewhere/between/genius/and/unhinged

$ ls -la
> ideas/          (too many)
> shipped/        (more than you'd expect)
> sleep/          (folder not found)
> excuses/        (empty)
```

Terminal Myth is a **digital forge** — built by builders, for builders. We live in the terminal, breathe in commits, and think in systems. Every project here started as a 2am idea that refused to die.

---

## 🔥 the vibe

| thing          | status                        |
|----------------|-------------------------------|
| coffee         | ☕☕☕ critical levels          |
| tabs open      | 47 and climbing               |
| bugs           | they're features now          |
| documentation  | you're reading it             |
| sleep schedule | a myth (fitting)              |
| shipping       | always                        |
| giving up      | not installed                 |

---

## 🛠️ stack of choice

```
Languages    →  TypeScript, Python, Rust (when we're feeling dangerous)
Frontend     →  Next.js, React, Tailwind (no, we don't use vanilla CSS. yes we judge you)
Backend      →  Node, FastAPI, whatever gets the job done at 3am
AI/ML        →  OpenAI, Anthropic, Replicate (we talk to robots for a living)
Web3         →  Solana, Ethereum, onchain everything
DB           →  Supabase, Postgres, Redis (sometimes just localStorage if we're cooked)
Deploy       →  Vercel, Railway, vibes
```

---

## 📜 the commandments

```
I.    ship fast or go home
II.   perfect is the enemy of deployed
III.  if it works on prod, it works
IV.   comments are for the weak* (*or when you'll forget in 6hrs)
V.    the best refactor is a rewrite
VI.   your tech debt is someone else's problem (that someone is future you)
VII.  we don't gatekeep. we open source.
VIII. gm is a lifestyle, not a greeting
IX.   the README is sacred
X.    we build what we wish existed
```

---

## 🚀 getting started

```bash
# clone the myth
git clone https://github.com/terminalmyth/whatever-this-is

# install the chaos
npm install

# pray to the runtime gods
npm run dev

# if it breaks
npm run dev --force  # doesn't do anything different but feels powerful
```

---

## 🌑 who builds here

Degens who got tired of waiting for someone else to build it.  
Coders who merge first and ask questions later.  
Builders who treat every side project like a startup.  
People who have more `.env` files than friends.  

If your GitHub contribution graph looks like a city skyline —  
**you're home.**

---

## 🤝 contributing

```bash
# the process
1. fork it
2. build something unhinged
3. open a PR with a based title
4. we'll review it (probably at midnight)
5. if it slaps, it ships
```

No gatekeeping. No ego. Just good code and bad sleep.

